{
  "doc_id": "25997",
  "text": "The orexin/hypocretin system is involved in the coordination of rhythmic daily functions, such as feeding and energy balance in fish [CITATION_1] . Taking in mind the orexigenic role of this regulator and its stimulatory effect on daily activity rhythms in the absence of other inputs [CITATION_2] , the possible role of orexin system in the physiology of certain brain areas involved in food intake and circadian regulation is intriguing. Orexin fibers found in some central oscillators, such as the pineal and the SCN, and other brain regions related to the regulation of activity/rest cycles [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . As a rule, orexins exert excitatory effects on various brain nuclei with the exception of a direct hyperpolarisation of clock cells in SCN during the night [CITATION_5] .",
